\begin_inset Formula $m\mid n$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n}/b_{m})$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-th power of a rational number.
 Then either
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(iCC) 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(h(x))$
\end_inset

 for some polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 with rational coefficients taking integral values at infinitely many integers;
 or
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(ii) equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\equiv a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{0}=b_{m}y^{m}+b_{m-1}y^{m-1}+\cdots+b_{0}\equiv g(y)
\]

\end_inset

has at most finitely many integral solutions.
\end_layout

